	<div>
		<h2>Eggs</h2>
		<p>Eggs are a versatile ingredient in the use for cooking.
			<br>They can be used for the purpose of making a meal.
			<br>Scrambled eggs for breakfast, an omlette for an evening tea.
			<br>They are also used in making treats such as buns and cakes.
		</p>

		<h3>Scrambled Eggs for One</h3>

		<h3>Ingredients</h3>
		<p>
			3 eggs preferably large eggs
			<br>1 and a half tablespoon of milk or cream, for loctose intolerance use lactose free milk substitute.
			<br>1 tablespoon of chives if desired
			<br>13 grams or half an once of butter / unsalted butter
			<br>salt and pepper to season
		</p>

		<h3>Scrambled Eggs Instructions</h3>
		<p>You will need:
			<br>A pan.
			<br>A hand held blitzing blender if available.
			<br>A tablespoon.
			<br>A teaspoon.
			<br>A fork.
			<br>A timer
			<br>Wooden Spatula.
			<br>Weighing Scales.
		</p>

		<p>Crack the eggs into a bowl and remove any shell bits that may have fallen into the mixture with a teaspoon.
			<br>Next add the 1 and a half tablespoon of  milk, cream or substitute desired and pepper.
			<br>Whisk together by using a hand held blitzing blender which will give a froth to the mixture which should make the scrambled eggs lighter on finish. Or use a fork as a whisk to combine the eggs and milk together.
			<br>Add the chives to the mixture and give a stir to combine.
			<br>
		<p>
			<br>Take the pan and place on the stove at a medium heat to warm it up.
			<br>Next add half the butter to the pan, roughly 6 grams and swirl it about the pan and make the base and sides have a coating.
			<br>When the butter has melted and looks foaming add the egg mixture with chives to the pan.
			<br>Using a wooden spatula or silicone utensil stir the mixture briskly in a back and forth motion getting right into the sides of the pan.
			<br>NEVER use Metal utensil as this will damage and scrape the pan.
			<br>This should take about 3 to 4 minutes.
		</p>
			<br>
		<p>
			When three quarters or slightly more of the egg mixture is a creamy looking solid mass and the last bit to a quarter is still liquidy. The pan may be removed from the heat and the eggs will continue cook.
			<br>Add the remainder of the butter and continue to stir briskly and scramble eggs until no liquid remains in the pan. Taste to check for seasoning and add salt if needed.
			<br>Move the contents of the pan to a plate. Add toast for the breakfast presentation.
		</p>

		<p>Reference: Maguire. N, 2018, <i>Home Economics for Life</i>, Dublin 12, Gill Books of M.H. Gill and Co.</p>
