		<h3>Roasted Aubergine / Eggplant and Tomato Curry</h3>

		<h3>Ingredients</h3>
		<p>
			300 grams of aubergines / eggplant
			<br>3 tablespoons of olive oil
			<br>1 onion
			<br>1 clove of garlic (crushed)
			<br>1 teaspoon of garam masala
			<br>1 teaspoon of turmeric
			<br>1 teaspoon of ground corriander
			<br>200ml from can of chooped tomatoes
			<br>200ml from can of coconut milk
			<br>sugar if desired
			<br>half a pack of corriander chopped
			<br>salt and pepper
		</p>

		<h3>Roasted Aubergine / Eggplant and Tomato Curry Instructions</h3>
		<p>You will need:
			<br>A roasting tin.
			<br>A large pot or casserole dish.
			<br>Chopping board.
			<br>Chopping knife.
			<br>Tin opener.
			<br>An Oven.
			<br>Aluminium foil (tin foil)
		</p>

		<p>
			Turn on the oven to 200 degrees celsius / 180 degrees celsius for fan assisted / gas mark 6
			<br>If using the fahrenheit temperature scale then the oven is set to 400 degrees fahrenheit
			<br>Line the roasting with tin foil. This should help prevent the aubergine / eggplant from sticking to the roasting while cooking
			<br>Using the chopping knife and board, cut the aubergine / eggplant in half length-ways and do the same again
			<br>Chop the aubergine / eggplant into rough mouth sized pieces
			<br>Place the aubergine / eggplant into the roasting tin
			<br>Drizzle 2 tablespoons of olive oil over the aubergine / eggplant and season with salt and pepper
			<br>Using hands mix the aubergine / eggplant well so that all the chunks are coated in the olive oil
			<br>Spread the aubergine / eggplant out as evenly spaced as possible and cook in the oven for 20 minutes until they turn a dark golden colour and are soft
			<br>
			<br>While the aubergine / eggplant is roasting in the oven start to make the sauce
			<br>Heat the remaining tablespoon of olive oil in a large pot or casserole dish on a medium to medium-high heat
			<br>Chop the onion and add it to the large pot
			<br>Make sure to stir the onion and coat it in all in the olive oil.
			<br>Cook the onion for roughly 5 to 6 minutes so that it is softening and turning golden
			<br>You can add a pinch of sugar at this point as it helps against the acidity of the onion
			<br>Add the crushed garlic, 1 teaspoon of garam masala, 1 teaspoon of turmeric and 1 teaspoon of ground corriander
			<br>Continue stirring to prevent the onions, garlic, garam masala, tumeric and corriander from burning.
			<br>Cook until the aromas of the spices are released
			<br>When the aubergine / eggplant is finished from cooking in the oven, add it to the onion mixture
			<br>Add the 200mls of chopped tin tomatoes and 200mls of coconut milk
			<br>Stir to combine all the mixed ingredients together
			<br>Make sure all the vegetable are well coated with the sauce
			<br>Turn down the heat to a gentle medium and place the lid on the pot
			<br>Allow for the mixture to simmer for about 20 to 25 minutes
			<br>Take the lid off and stir continuously for 5 minutes to help thicken the sauce
			<br>Serve in a bowl with rice or enjoy on its own
			<br>Add chopped corriander to garnish
		</p>

		<p>
			Reference: Collins, C. 2016,<i>BBC Good Food Magazine</i>, Priest, A. Immediate Media, Date Viewed: 12/1/2022, URL: https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/roasted-aubergine-tomato-curry,<a href="https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/roasted-aubergine-tomato-curry">BBC Good Food</a>
		</p>
