	<div>
		<h2>Lactose Free</h2>
		<p>
			Choosing a lactose free recipe can be difficult, especially when looking for a treat.
			<br>There tends to be many chocolate products available that mainly contain some form of milk chocolate.
			<br>Other than baked goods it may be hard to find a little pick-me-up and even then they could contain cream.
			<br>This recipe while it may be time-consuming could offer that little indulgence.
		</p>

		<h3>Chocolate, orange and hazelnut cake</h3>
		<h3>Ingredients</h3>
		<p>
			175mls of light coloured olive oil
			<br>Some extra olive oil for greasing the tin
			<br>140grams of hazelnuts
			<br>100mls of orange juice
			<br>The zest of an orange
			<br>140grams of sef-raising flour(sieved)
			<br>half a teaspoon of baking powder(sieved)
			<br>50grams of cocoa powder(sieved)
			<br>3 large eggs
			<br>175grams light brown muscavado sugar
			<br>
			<br>100grams caster sugar (for the syrup)
			<br>100mls water (for the syrup)
			<br>half freshly squeezed orange (for the syrup)
			<br>
			<br>75mls of orange juice (for the chocolate topping)
			<br>100grams of diary free dark (chocolate for the chocolate)
		</p>

		<h3>Chocolate, orange and hazelnut cake Instructions</h3>
		<p>You will need:
			<br>An Oven.
			<br>An electric hand whisker or hand whisk.
			<br>A tablespoon.
			<br>A teaspoon.
			<br>Wooden spoon.
			<br>A timer
			<br>Set of bowls.
			<br>Weighing Scales.
			<br>Sieve
			<br>cocktail stick, toothpick / small skewer
			<br>juicer
			<br>zester
			<br>Food processor
			<br>baking parchment paper
			<br>rolling pin
			<br>jug
			<br>wire-rack
		</p>

		<p>
			Turn on the oven to 180 degrees celsius / 160 degrees celsius for fan / gas mark 4
			<br>If using the fahrenheit temperature scale then the oven is set to 350 degrees fahrenheit
			<br>Using a little of the olive oil grease a loaf tin and line the tin with baking parchment paper
			<br>Using a food processor grind 140grams of hazelnuts until they resemble course breadcrumbs
			<br>Alternatively you can place the hazelnuts in a plastic ziplock food bag (other brands available), place a tea-towel over the bag and beat with rolling pin or bottom of a pot until crushed
			<br>Add the 140grams of hazelnuts to a bowl, with the 140grams of sef-raising flour sieved, 50grams of cocoa powder sieved, half a teaspoon of baking powder sieved and the zest of an orange
			<br>Mix these ingredients until they are evenly combined with each other
			<br>Add the 175mls of olive oil and 100mls of orange juice to a jug and mix together thoroughly
			<br>In a separate bowl crack in the 3 large eggs and add 175grams of light brown muscavado sugar
			<br>Using an electric hand mixer whisk together the eggs and sugar for roughly 5 to 10 minutes or until the mixture has tripled in volume and holds a little flopped peak shape
			<br>Slowly add the oil and orange juice mixture to the whisked eggs and combine by folding using a wooden spoon
			<br>Folding is done by gently stirring the mixture and drawing the wooden spoon back towards you
			<br>Add the flour mixture to the egg mixture in 3 to 4 stages
			<br>Gently shake the first stage of the flour mixture into the egg mixture so that is evenly dispersed in the bowl
			<br>Again fold each stage of the flour mixture into the egg mixture until the eggs have absorbed and combined with the flour
			<br>Pour the egg batter mixture into the earlier prepared loaf tin and bake in the oven for 50 to 55 minutes
			<br>During the last 10 to 15 minutes of oven cooking time prepare the syrup
			<br>Using a small pot combine 100grams of caster sugar and half of a freshly squeezed orange and heat until the mixture begins thickening from a running consistency
			<br>When the cake is out of the oven prick the top the cake everywhere with a small skewer
			<br>Pour 5 tablespoons of the syrup mixture over the top of the cake
			<br>Leave the cake to cool in the tin for 15 minutes and prepare the cake topping
			<br>Add 75mls of orange juice in a small pot until it simmers.
			<br>Place 100grams of dairy free dark chocolate in a bowl
			<br>Pour the heated orange juice over the dairy free dark chocolate and mix until the chocolate and orange juice combine into a smooth mixture
			<br>Leave the chocolate aside to cool down for about 15 minutes
			<br>Set the cae on a wire-rake to continue to cool down
			<br>Once the chocolate mixture has cooled spread it on top of the cake
		</p>
		<p>
			Reference: Kimber, E. 2015,December,<i>BBC Good Food Magazine</i>, Priest, A. Immediate Media Co., Date Viewed: 12/1/2022, URL: https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/chocolate-orange-hazelnut-cake,<a href="https://www.bbcgoodfood.com/recipes/chocolate-orange-hazelnut-cake">BBC Good Food</a>
		</p>
